## 1. Pre-Requisites

Before touching any Claude Code configuration, install these globally on the target machine:

| Tool | Version | Install Command | Verification |
|------|---------|-----------------|------------|
| Node.js LTS | 20.x+ | Download from [nodejs.org](https://nodejs.org/) or `winget install OpenJS.NodeJS` | `node --version` |
| Git for Windows | Latest | Download from [git-scm.com](https://git-scm.com/download/win) | `git --version` |
| npm | Bundled with Node | Comes with Node.js | `npm --version` |

**Then:**
1. Clone the project repository to its permanent location: `git clone <repo-url> C:\Projects\3D_Astroids`
2. Ensure Node.js is in your **system** PATH (not just user PATH), as hooks run before the shell env is fully initialized.
3. **Engine stack TBD.** Once the stack is chosen, run the appropriate install command (e.g., `npm install` if using a Node-based build).

---

## 2. Installation Order (Critical)

Several steps have hard dependencies on files created in earlier steps. **Follow this exact order.**

| Step | Action | Creates / Configures | Depends On |
|------|--------|----------------------|------------|
| 2.1 | Install Claude Code CLI globally | `claude` command | Node.js |
| 2.2 | Create/update global `settings.json` | `~/.claude/settings.json` | — |
| 2.3 | Create status line script | `~/.claude/3dastroids-statusline.cjs` | — |
| 2.4 | Create project `.claude/` directory | `C:\Projects\3D_Astroids\.claude\` | Git clone |
| 2.5 | Create project hooks | `session-start.cjs`, `pre-tool-use.cjs`, `post-tool-use.cjs` | Step 2.4 |
| 2.6 | Create code style rules | `code-style.md` | Step 2.4 |
| 2.7 | Create project `settings.json` | `C:\Projects\3D_Astroids\.claude\settings.json` | Steps 2.3, 2.5 |
| 2.8 | Replace `<YourUser>` placeholders | Global settings.json, project settings.json, `CLAUDE.md` | Steps 2.2, 2.7 |
| 2.9 | Create memory directory + index | `MEMORY.md` + `.md` files | — |
| 2.10 | Create auto-save cron job | Session-only cron (50-min interval) | Step 2.9 |
| 2.11 | First run + trust dialog | `~/.claude.json` (auto-generated) | Steps 2.1–2.10 |
| 2.12 | **Restart Claude Code** | Status line becomes active | Step 2.11 |

**Why this order matters:**
- The global `settings.json` (Step 2.2) references the status line script (Step 2.3). The script must exist before Claude Code first reads the config.
- The project `settings.json` (Step 2.7) references hooks that live in `.claude/hooks/` (Step 2.5).
- The trust dialog (Step 2.11) creates an auto-generated `~/.claude.json` entry that cannot be pre-configured; it must be accepted interactively.
- The `statusLine` configuration is **cached at process startup** and requires a full restart (Step 2.12) to take effect.

---

### 2.8 Replace `<YourUser>` Placeholders

After creating the files in Steps 2.2, 2.7, and 2.8, replace the literal string `<YourUser>` with your actual Windows username in **all three files**:

| File | Field(s) to update |
|------|-------------------|
| `C:\Users\<YourUser>\.claude\settings.json` | `statusLine.command` only |
| `C:\Projects\3D_Astroids\.claude\settings.json` | `statusLine.command` only |
| `C:\Projects\3D_Astroids\CLAUDE.md` | Auto-Save memory path (`C:\Users\<YourUser>\.claude\projects\...`) |

**Do not** replace anything in `additionalDirectories` — those use absolute paths without placeholders.

**Why:** If left as `<YourUser>`, the status line script path breaks silently, and auto-save writes memories to a non-existent folder.

---

### 2.10 Create Auto-Save Cron Job

The auto-save system requires a cron job. In Claude Code, run:

```
/CronCreate {"cron": "*/50 * * * *", "prompt": "🔄 Memory save is now taking place… Check for new/updated memories in C:\\Users\\%USERNAME%\\.claude\\projects\\C--Projects-3D-Astroids\\memory\\. Write them. Post a recap. Confirm with ✅.", "recurring": true}
```

**Important:** Claude Code cron jobs are **session-only**. They are lost when Claude Code exits. You must recreate this cron job every time you start a new session.

**Verification:** Run `/CronList` — you should see one entry with `cron: */50 * * * *`.

---

## 3. Infrastructure Setup

### 3.1 Install Claude Code CLI (Global)

**Use the npm package. Do NOT use the native Windows `.exe` installer — it has known `statusLine` rendering bugs.**

```powershell
npm install -g @anthropic-ai/claude-code
```

Verify: `claude --version`

**Note:** If `claude --version` is not recognized, open a new PowerShell window and try again — npm global PATH changes may require a fresh session.

---

### 3.2 Global Settings (`~/.claude/settings.json`)

**Path:** `C:\Users\<YourUser>\.claude\settings.json`

This file is read on every Claude Code startup. It controls global plugins, permissions, effort level, and the status line.

**CRITICAL:** Replace `<YourUser>` with your actual Windows username in the `statusLine.command` path.

**CRITICAL:** In `statusLine.command`, use **forward slashes** (`C:/Users/...`) even though this is Windows. Claude Code's internal command runner uses Git Bash semantics, which silently mangles backslash escapes and breaks the path. This was a three-hour root-cause investigation from the Donkey Kong project (2026-05-30).

The global status line is intentionally left pointing at the Donkey Kong script so that project is untouched. The 3D Astroids project overrides this with its own project-level `settings.json`.

```json
{
  "permissions": {
    "additionalDirectories": [
      "C:\\Projects",
      "C:\\Projects\\3D_Astroids"
    ],
    "defaultMode": "auto"
  },
  "enabledPlugins": {
    "andrej-karpathy-skills@karpathy-skills": true,
    "remember@claude-plugins-official": true,
    "superpowers@claude-plugins-official": true,
    "frontend-design@claude-plugins-official": true,
    "claude-md-management@claude-plugins-official": true,
    "context7@claude-plugins-official": true,
    "chrome-devtools-mcp@claude-plugins-official": true,
    "playwright@claude-plugins-official": true,
    "coderabbit@claude-plugins-official": true,
    "feature-dev@claude-plugins-official": true,
    "explanatory-output-style@claude-plugins-official": true,
    "code-simplifier@claude-plugins-official": true,
    "skill-creator@claude-plugins-official": true,
    "ralph-loop@claude-plugins-official": true,
    "commit-commands@claude-plugins-official": true
  },
  "extraKnownMarketplaces": {
    "karpathy-skills": {
      "source": {
        "source": "github",
        "repo": "forrestchang/andrej-karpathy-skills"
      },
      "autoUpdate": true
    }
  },
  "effortLevel": "xhigh",
  "skipDangerousModePermissionPrompt": true,
  "theme": "dark-daltonized",
  "statusLine": {
    "type": "command",
    "command": "node C:/Users/<YourUser>/.claude/dk-statusline.cjs",
    "padding": 1,
    "refreshInterval": 60,
    "hideVimModeIndicator": false
  }
}
```

**What this does:**
- `defaultMode: auto` — Claude Code asks for permission on potentially destructive actions but auto-approves reads and safe edits. This avoids `--yesToAll` bypass while keeping workflow smooth.
- `additionalDirectories` — Allows Claude Code to access the project even when launched from a different working directory.
- `enabledPlugins` — Activates marketplace skills, remembering, feature development, code review, etc.
- `effortLevel: xhigh` — Tells Claude Code to use maximum reasoning depth for all responses.
- `statusLine` — Global fallback. 3D Astroids overrides this at the project level.

---

### 3.3 Status Line Script (`~/.claude/3dastroids-statusline.cjs`)

**Path:** `C:\Users\<YourUser>\.claude\3dastroids-statusline.cjs`

This Node.js script receives JSON on stdin after every assistant turn and prints a one-line status string. It is a **separate, project-specific script** so the Donkey Kong script remains untouched.

**Why `.cjs`:** The project may later declare `"type": "module"` in `package.json`, so `.js` files would be treated as ESM. This script uses `require()` (CommonJS), so it **must** have the `.cjs` extension.

**Why forward slashes:** The `command` string in `settings.json` uses forward slashes (`C:/Users/...`) because Git Bash (used internally by Claude Code) silently mangles Windows backslashes.

```javascript
const fs = require('fs');
const path = require('path');
const { execSync } = require('child_process');

/**
 * ============================================================================
 * My Rules — Status Line Script Notes
 * ============================================================================
 * Purpose:
 *   Custom Claude Code status line that displays the last memory-save time,
 *   model name, context-window percentage, and session cost in the CLI bottom
 *   bar after every assistant turn.
 *
 * Setup:
 *   - Lives at C:/Users/User101/.claude/3dastroids-statusline.cjs
 *   - Referenced from settings.json via "statusLine": { "type": "command",
 *     "command": "node C:/Users/User101/.claude/3dastroids-statusline.cjs" }
 *   - Reads the newest .md mtime from the memory directory to show 💾 HH:MM.
 *
 * Issues (2026-05-30, inherited from Donkey Kong):
 *   - The status bar showed only the default "auto mode on" text.
 *   - The custom 💾 output never appeared, even after restart, even though
 *     trust settings were correct, hooks were enabled, and the script worked
 *     perfectly when tested manually in PowerShell.
 *
 * Fix:
 *   - The "command" path in settings.json was using Windows backslashes:
 *       "node C:\\Users\\User101\\.claude\\dk-statusline.cjs"
 *   - Claude Code's internal command runner uses Git Bash semantics on
 *     Windows, which treat backslashes as escape characters and silently
 *     mangle/destroy the path. The script path became invalid and the
 *     statusLine fell back to the default bar with no visible error.
 *   - Changed the path to forward slashes (which Node.js accepts on Windows):
 *       "node C:/Users/User101/.claude/3dastroids-statusline.cjs"
 *
 * Gotchas:
 *   - ALWAYS use forward slashes in the "command" field of statusLine on
 *     Windows, even for absolute paths.
 *   - Manual PowerShell testing does NOT reveal this bug — the internal
 *     Claude Code runner uses different shell semantics.
 *   - The script is spawned with JSON on stdin after every assistant message.
 *   - ANSI colour codes are supported in the output.
 * ============================================================================
 */

/**
 * 3D Astroids — Claude Code Status Line
 *
 * Receives JSON from Claude Code on stdin after every assistant message.
 * Prints a single-line status string to stdout that renders in the
 * bottom status bar.
 *
 * Fields used from stdin JSON:
 *   - model.display_name
 *   - context_window.used_percentage
 *   - cost.total_cost_usd
 *
 * Custom field (read from disk):
 *   - Last memory save time (mtime of newest .md in memory dir)
 */

const MEMORY_DIR = path.join(
  process.env.USERPROFILE || process.env.HOME || '',
  '.claude', 'projects', 'C--Projects-3D-Astroids', 'memory'
);

function getLastMemorySave() {
  try {
    const files = fs.readdirSync(MEMORY_DIR).filter(f => f.endsWith('.md'));
    if (files.length === 0) return '—';

    let newest = { file: '', mtime: 0 };
    for (const f of files) {
      const stat = fs.statSync(path.join(MEMORY_DIR, f));
      if (stat.mtimeMs > newest.mtime) {
        newest = { file: f, mtime: stat.mtimeMs };
      }
    }

    const d = new Date(newest.mtime);
    const hh = String(d.getHours()).padStart(2, '0');
    const mm = String(d.getMinutes()).padStart(2, '0');
    return `${hh}:${mm}`;
  } catch (e) {
    return 'err';
  }
}

/**
 * My Rules — Git Status Indicator
 * Purpose: Show current branch and uncommitted file count so the user
 *   knows at a glance if work is unsaved or if they're on the wrong branch.
 * Setup: Runs `git branch --show-current` and `git status --short` via
 *   child_process.execSync. cwd defaults to the project root.
 * Issues: None yet.
 * Fix: Inherited from Donkey Kong setup (2026-05-30).
 * Gotchas:
 *   - If cwd is not inside a git repo, returns '—'.
 *   - Dirty count is the number of lines from `git status --short`.
 *   - Uses ● (bullet) for dirty, ✓ for clean to stay compact.
 */
function getGitInfo() {
  try {
    const branch = execSync('git branch --show-current', {
      cwd: process.cwd(),
      encoding: 'utf8',
      stdio: ['pipe', 'pipe', 'ignore'],
      timeout: 1000
    }).trim();

    if (!branch) return '—';

    const short = execSync('git status --short', {
      cwd: process.cwd(),
      encoding: 'utf8',
      stdio: ['pipe', 'pipe', 'ignore'],
      timeout: 1000
    }).trim();

    const dirtyCount = short ? short.split('\n').length : 0;
    const indicator = dirtyCount > 0
      ? `\x1b[33m●${dirtyCount}\x1b[0m` // yellow bullet + count
      : '\x1b[32m✓\x1b[0m';            // green checkmark

    return `${branch} ${indicator}`;
  } catch (e) {
    return '—';
  }
}

let input = '';
process.stdin.setEncoding('utf8');

process.stdin.on('data', chunk => {
  input += chunk;
});

process.stdin.on('end', () => {
  let data = {};
  try {
    data = JSON.parse(input || '{}');
  } catch {
    // ignore malformed JSON
  }

  const model = data.model?.display_name || 'Claude';
  const ctxPct = Math.floor(data.context_window?.used_percentage || 0);
  const cost = data.cost?.total_cost_usd || 0;
  const lastSave = getLastMemorySave();
  const gitInfo = getGitInfo();

  // ANSI colours (green for low ctx, yellow for mid, red for high)
  let ctxColor = '\x1b[32m'; // green
  if (ctxPct > 70) ctxColor = '\x1b[33m'; // yellow
  if (ctxPct > 90) ctxColor = '\x1b[31m'; // red
  const reset = '\x1b[0m';

  // Compact status line
  const status = `💾 ${lastSave} | ${gitInfo} | ${model} | ${ctxColor}${ctxPct}%${reset} ctx | $${cost.toFixed(2)}`;
  console.log(status);
});

// Safety timeout: if stdin never closes (shouldn't happen), emit anyway
setTimeout(() => {
  if (!process.stdin.destroyed) {
    const lastSave = getLastMemorySave();
    const gitInfo = getGitInfo();
    console.log(`💾 ${lastSave} | ${gitInfo} | Claude | ?% ctx`);
  }
}, 5000);
```

---

### 3.3a Status Line Debug Helper (`~/.claude/3dastroids-statusline-debug.cjs`)

Create a minimal debug script alongside the production status line. It logs every invocation and the first 200 characters of stdin to `%USERPROFILE%\\claude-3dastroids-statusline-debug.log`. This is invaluable when the status bar shows only `auto mode on` even though the script works in PowerShell.

```javascript
const fs = require('fs');
const path = require('path');

const LOG = path.join(process.env.USERPROFILE || '', 'claude-3dastroids-statusline-debug.log');
const now = new Date().toISOString();

fs.appendFileSync(LOG, `[${now}] STATUSLINE INVOKED\n`);

let input = '';
process.stdin.setEncoding('utf8');
process.stdin.on('data', chunk => input += chunk);
process.stdin.on('end', () => {
  fs.appendFileSync(LOG, `[${now}] STDIN received: ${input.slice(0, 200)}...\n`);
  console.log(`💾 debug | test`);
});

setTimeout(() => {
  fs.appendFileSync(LOG, `[${now}] TIMEOUT fallback\n`);
  console.log(`💾 timeout | test`);
}, 5000);
```

**How to use:**
1. Temporarily change `statusLine.command` in `C:\\Projects\\3D_Astroids\\.claude\\settings.json` to point at `3dastroids-statusline-debug.cjs`.
2. Restart Claude Code.
3. Check the log file.
   - **Log exists** → the command path is correct; the issue is in the production script.
   - **Log does not exist** → the path is broken (usually Windows backslashes). Fix with forward slashes.
4. Point `statusLine.command` back to the production script and restart.

